Project : investigate a Dataset¶

For this project, the aim is to conduct a data analysis and share my findings on a chosen data set.

I will follow the classic data analysis process :

  • Gather the data
  • Wrangle the data
  • Brainstorm on some possible questions to investigate
  • Explore the data
  • Draw conclusions
  • Communicate

The chosen dataset for this project is from Gapfinder World. It represents "information about how people live their lives in different countries, tracked across the years, and on a number of different indicators".

Questions answered in this study:

  • How is income distributed in the world in 2020 comapred to 1950 ? (Visual = Histogram)
  • How did life expectency change through time for each region ? (Visual = Line chart)
  • Do countries with higher income achieve higher human developpement index ? (Visual = Bar chart)
  • Is there any correlation between inqueality and corruption rates in europe ? (Visual = Scatter plot)

Author : Souhail YOUSSEFI

Step 1 : Gather the data¶

Chosen indicators (per country):

  • Total population
  • Income per person (GDP/capita, PPP dollar inflation-adjusted)
  • Life expectency (years)
  • Literacy rate adult (total percent of people ages 15 and above)
  • Number of personal computers
  • Human developpement index (Health, Education, Living standards)
  • Gini coefficient (inequality, a higher number means more inequality)
  • CPI (Corruption perception index, higher values mean less corruption)

(downloaded in separate csv files)

Step 2 : Wrangle the data¶

In this part the aim is to :

  • Have a quick look at each csv.
  • Assess (identify problems in data quality): number of columns and rows, format, duplicates, missing values.
  • Clean the csv files.
  • Merge the csv files.
  • Re-asses the csv files.

#Creates a function to get the name of each dataframe
def get_df_name(df):
    name =[x for x in globals() if globals()[x] is df][0]
    return name

Step 2.2 : Reorganize the data¶

At the end it should look like this : {Country, Year, Indicator 1 Value, Indicator 2 Value, … }.

To deal with this, for every metric we will do the following :

  • Create a new dataframe with country, year and indicator name
  • Fill for every year the indicator value for all the countries (for exemple all population values for 1800 in all countries, then the next loop would append this with all population values for 1801 in all countries and so on until the end.
  • Store each new edited file in order to merge them all afterwards
In [8]:
for name in names :
    labels = np.array(['country', 'year', get_df_name(name)])
    df = pd.DataFrame(columns = labels)
    years = name.iloc[:,1:].columns.values
    for year in years:
        df2 = name[['country', year]].copy()
        df2.rename(columns={year:get_df_name(name)}, inplace=True)
        df2.insert(1, 'year', year) 
        df = df.append(df2)

    file_name = get_df_name(name)+'_edited.csv'
    df.to_csv(file_name, index=False)  
    
population_new = pd.read_csv('population_edited.csv')
print(population_new.shape)

Research question 1 : How is income distributed in the world in 2020 compared to 1950?¶

plt.ylabel('Number of countries');

Partial conclusion 1 :¶

  • Income doesn't have the same distribution in 2020 compared to 1950
  • Income in 1950 is less spread and more skewed to the right compared to 2020 : this means that inequalities between countries increased through time.
  • Generally countries have increased their income per person compared to 1950

Research question 2 : How did life expectency change through time for each region ?¶

In [18]:
years = final_df['year'].unique()
regions_name = final_df['regions'].unique()
life_expectency = pd.DataFrame(years, columns=['year'])

#Calculate mean life expectency per year and per region
for region in regions_name :
    life_expectency_per_region = pd.DataFrame(columns=['year', region])
    for year in years :
        mean = int(final_df.query('year == @year').query('regions == @region').life_expectency.mean())
        new_row = pd.DataFrame({'year': [year], region:[mean]})
        life_expectency_per_region = life_expectency_per_region.append(new_row, ignore_index=True)
    life_expectency = pd.merge(life_expectency, life_expectency_per_region, how='outer', on=['year'])

#convert years from float to int
life_expectency['year'] = life_expectency['year'].astype(int)
life_expectency=life_expectency.set_index('year')

In [20]:
moving_avg_life_expectency = life_expectency

for region in life_expectency.columns.values :
    for year in range (int(life_expectency.index[4]),int(life_expectency.index[-1])):
        moving_avg_life_expectency.loc[year, region] = (life_expectency.loc[year,region]+
                                                        life_expectency.loc[year-1,region]+
                                                        life_expectency.loc[year-2,region]+
                                                        life_expectency.loc[year-3,region]+
                                                        life_expectency.loc[year-4,region])/5

Partial conclusion 2 :¶

  • Until 1870's, life expectency was relatively stable for all regions.
  • From 1870's to 1970's there was as a sharp increase of life expectency. Europe started this raise earlier than the other regions. The other regions compensated this gap by 1970's.
  • From 1970's, the increase continued but with a lower gradient.
  • The relative ranking between regions changed around 1935. Asia went from last to 3rd. Ranking today is : Europe(1st), Americas (2nd), Asia(3rd), Africas(4th).
  • The study zoomed on some particular points :
    • General drop around 1918 (possibly related to world war I ?)
    • Drop in Europe around 1940's (possibly related to world war II ?)
    • Africa showed a slow-down in the 2000's (?)

df_question_3 = final_df.query('year >= 1990 & year <= 2018')

#calculate mean income and hdi per country from 1990 to 2018
country_name = human_developpement_index['country'].unique()
df_question_3_countries = pd.DataFrame(columns=['country','income','hdi'])
for country in country_name :
    mean_income_per_country = df_question_3.query('country == @country').income.mean()
    mean_hdi_per_country = df_question_3.query('country == @country').human_developpement_index.mean()
    new_row = pd.DataFrame({'country': [country], 'income': [mean_income_per_country],'hdi': [mean_hdi_per_country]})
    #make sure to do df= df.append()
    df_question_3_countries = df_question_3_countries.append(new_row, ignore_index=True)

  • The answer seems to be yes. Human developpement index is on average higher for higher incomes than lower incomes.
  • Median income is 8515 GDP/Capita, PPP dollar inflation-adjusted
  • It could makes sens since human developpement index is based on three dimensions (health level, educational level and living standard) which are all in some sort of way related to income.
